      "writtenOn": "2019-01-03T22:51:56Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I haven\u0027t thought too much about it (considering it is a very niche use case). My thoughts so far:\n  1. As you\u0027ve noticed node key namespace is hierarchical.\n  2. I imagine we can import another project node graph into a key subspace (PROJECT, \u003cname\u003e, *). \n  3. Then BUILDER_REF nodes of an external project would be (PROJECT, \u003cname\u003e, BUCKET, \u003cb\u003e, BUILDER_REF, \u003cn\u003e) (and the one without the bucket).\n  4. keys.builder_ref can learn to understand some additional syntax, e.g. \"[infra]/ci/builder\" will result in (PROJECT, \u0027infra\u0027, BUCKET, \u0027ci\u0027, BUILDER_REF, \u0027builder\u0027). (\u0027[]\u0027 is needed to distinguish between \"\u003cproject\u003e/\u003cbuilder\u003e\" (a bucketless reference to a builder in another project) and \"\u003cbucket\u003e/\u003cbuilder\u003e\" (bucket-scoped reference to a builder within main project) references. (We can also bikeshed this syntax ad infinitum).\n\nI\u0027m not planning on doing this any time soon, but I believe it should be relatively simple.",
      "parentUuid": "8e8ad3ce_c1538eb9",
      "revId": "a7f80a98e5b5ad6f4cdea341fd2e3a1726c04773",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
